  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in the United States and in many other jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves three steps: placement, layering, and integration.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily under the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). The penalties for money laundering can be severe, including:\n\n1. **Fines**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face substantial fines. The amount can vary depending on the specifics of the case but can reach up to $500,000 or more.\n2. **Prison Sentences**: Felony convictions for money laundering can result in lengthy prison sentences, often up to 20 years per count. In some cases, sentences can be even longer, especially if the laundering is associated with other serious crimes like drug trafficking or terrorism.\n3. **Asset Forfeiture**: The government can seize assets that are involved in or derived from money laundering activities.\n\nAdditionally, other consequences may include loss of professional licenses, damage to personal and business reputation, and difficulties in securing future employment.\n\nIt's important to note that laws and penalties may vary by country, but in most jurisdictions, money laundering is treated as a serious criminal offense.",
